<TITLE>AQHA to celebrate the Charro lifestyle</TITLE>
<TEXT>
Women compete with synchronization in colorful dresses while riding side saddle while the men perform the more masculine events of La Charreria the official sport of Mexico And it s all done so gracefully atop a quarter horse The new Nacidos Charro Born Charro exhibit celebrating the Mexican rodeo is now open at the American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame and Museum where it will continue through July 29 It s our first bilingual exhibit said Crystal Phares the AQHA curator who worked to create the exhibit with Melissa Loftin community outreach liaison We want to celebrate the quarter horse throughout the world La Charerria is quite different in pageantry from the American rodeo We wanted it be colorful and tell the story of the family values and tradition Loftin said La Charreria is so much more than a rodeo Indeed the first thing a visitor sees when walking in is a colorfully dressed woman who competes as an escaranauz a mounted lady representing the women s event drill teams on horseback It s like synchronized swimming on quarter horses Phares said The exhibit was a natural fit for the museum according to Phares and Loftin We have an international membership Loftin said La Charreria is quarter horses and we re about quarter horses The exhibit is included with general admission to the museum which hopes to attract a diverse population to see the facility s many exhibits and learn more about the history of the quarter horse and their Hall of Fame as well as the Mexican sport The exhibit hits all levels from people who enjoy history horses Mexico culture and just about anyone Phares said It includes artifacts from the 1800s to the present The event is a festival and about family Loftin said Their fathers and grandfathers were Charro cowboys They are cowboys for life Charros were the gentlemen This is very much the gentlemen s sport Many of the nine La Charreria events are pictured in the exhibit with two events recognized by the AQHA bull trailing and reining There is a difference in competitions from what our American European and Australian memberships know as rodeo in the competitions and it always has a parade Loftin said The color and costumes are on display along with the typical cooking utensils used during the festivals We hope the exhibit expresses the life speed and color Phares said It s so vibrant 
